1. Background

1.1 What’s so hard about predicting elections?

  1. The nature of presidential campagins in the United States.
    Presidential campaigns start well ahead of the actual voting. This allows for various circumstances to evolve continuously, causing voters’ stance on issues to also change accordingly. This means that the results of a poll or sample survey have a very limited lifespan and the data could be nonrepresntative of the population very soon after it’s gathered.

  2. Not all votes are created equal.
    Since US elections still utilize the elctoral college, the number of vote does not determine the outcome of the elections. Instead, the outcome is determined by the number of textbf{electoral} votes. This add further complexity as not all votes are as impactful as others.

  3. Large population with high variability.
    Due to the massive size of the USA and its large population there is high variability in attitudes and opinions even at the state level. This means that finding a respresentative sample is more diffcult and adds a hidden bias to any data gathered. Additionally, there are logistical difficulties like repeat polling, social desriability bias (surveyees not answering hoenstly in fear of judgement by the surveryor).

1.2 Nate Silver’s prediction was “righter” than others. How did he do it?

  1. Letting the data speak for itself.
    Silver spoke on how Clinton’s polling numbers in the midwest were lower than those for the former democratic president, Obama. These poor numbers were largely dismissed by analysts, however, Silver was not so quick to do so himself. By letting the data speak for itself and investigating this trend he was able to overcome a weakness that was exposed in other models.

  2. Assuming correlated errors.
    After considering the uncertainty of lots of undecided voters and the uncertainty due to polling procedures, Silver simulated errors based on regional and demographic information. This helped him account for more errors and uncertainty, which in turn provided a more accurate representation of the population.

1.3 What made this election so unpredictable, and how what can we do to improve in the coming elections?

To do so we created 2 new variables; county_winner and state_winner. These variables identify the winner by finding the candidate with the highest proportion of votes on the county and state level.

3. Dimenionality Reduction

Now that we’ve cleaned up and aggregated our census data, we’re going to analyse the variables. By doing principal compenent analysis (PCA), we will also try to reduce the variables in our data. This is essentially done by selecting the variables that differ the most from region to region, since those differences are likely to explain differences in voting behaviour regionally.

When performing PCA there is always the question of whether or not to scale and center our data. Since we have a wide range of variables measured in a wide range of units we chose to scale our data. This would mean that the variance of each variable is not relative to the type of measurement, rather the variance would be uniform for all the predictors. As for centering out data, we always favor that approach because it specifies the direction of each principal component and minimizes the chance of error.

5. Classification

For classification we want to combine our county winners with our census data.

Next, we partition data into 20% testing and 80% training:

And define 10 cross-validations folds:

And use the following error rate function:

First, we’ll try to classify using a decision tree. We’ll use soft classification, meaning determining the candidate who will recieve the vote based off demographic data rather than determining the proabability of voting for each candidate. We’ll draw the original tree and the pruned, more simplified tree.

#draw tree before pruning
tree.cl <- tree(candidate ~., data = trn.cl)
par(mar = c(2, 0, 0, 0))
draw.tree(tree.cl, nodeinfo = TRUE,cex = 0.7)

#prune tree with cv.tree
tree.cl.cv <- cv.tree(tree.cl, rand = folds, K = nfold, FUN = prune.misclass)

#draw tree after pruning
opt.trees = which(tree.cl.cv$dev == min(tree.cl.cv$dev))
best.size.cv <- min(tree.cl.cv$size[opt.trees])
pruned.tree <- prune.tree(tree.cl, best = best.size.cv)
par(mar = c(2, 0, 0, 0))
draw.tree(pruned.tree, nodeinfo=TRUE, cex =0.7)

#calculate error rates for train and test
records[1,1] <- calc_error_rate(predict(pruned.tree, data = trn.cl[,-1], type = "class"), trn.cl$candidate)
records[1,2] <- calc_error_rate(predict(pruned.tree, data = tst.cl[,-1], type = "class"), tst.cl$candidate)

Pruning the tree helps us understand the main demographic attributes that determine whether Clinton or Trump would win without losing too much accuracy in classification. This not only simplifies the modelbut also makes it easy to interpret. A couple of the straightforward factors affecting the election are minority percentages and average income.

Our next classification method is logistic regression. Again we’ll try to predict county votes based off demographic data.

Finally, we’ll run K-fold cross validation and select the best regularization parameter for the logistic regression. We’ll use LASSO as our penalty and work to minimize that parameter.

#fitting cv.glmnet
x <- model.matrix(candidate~., trn.cl)[,-1]
y <- ifelse(trn.cl$candidate=="Donald Trump",1,0)
set.seed(10)
lasso.cl <- cv.glmnet(x, y, alpha = 1, family = "binomial")

#best regularization parameter
bestlam <- lasso.cl$lambda.1se
bestlam

We see that the LASSO method gives us the least test error and is a lot more consistent with the training error, meaning it both fits the training data and the test data well. It follows that the tree and log-regression classification are a lot more bias since they fit the training data really well but poorly fit the test data.
